    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-09T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-09T22:00:00-05:00" n="285"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/890: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-10T12:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 10, 1938—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 10—3
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>15. Department’s 384, December 30, 3 p.m.,<note n="13" xml:id="d285fn13">
                        <ref target="frus1937v04#pg_426">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1937, Vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 426</ref>.</note> Japanese military
                    jurisdiction over American nationals in China. I brought up this <pb facs="0233"
                        n="229" xml:id="pg_229"/> matter informally and as on my own initiative with
                    the Minister for Foreign Affairs, this morning when discussing other matters.
                    Hirota said that the Japanese military in Shanghai had been obliged to issue
                    these regulations to protect themselves from the acts of irresponsible
                    foreigners in Shanghai but he said that the Japanese military authorities
                    perfectly understood the status of extraterritorial foreigners and he thought
                    that there was not the slightest intention of applying these regulations to
                    Americans. He did not seem disposed to give me specific assurances on this point
                    but took the position that we would have no cause for complaint. I pointed out
                    informally that any attempt on the part of any Japanese agencies to [assert at?]
                    Shanghai jurisdiction over American nationals in China could not be recognized
                    or countenanced by the United States Government.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
